\begin{theorem}[{\cite[Theorem~3]{Selberg:1974}, p.~208}]
Let $f$ be a holomorphic function on $\mathbb C$, with an analytic extension to all of its branch points (including possibly infinity). If it has no pole at any point except for one, then there exists another such point which can be chosen so as not to lie in the interior or exterior of some closed contour which encloses two other disjoint closed sets of positive measure, and whose radius does not exceed half-width of this set plus its boundary. Moreover, if these are the only singularities of order greater than zero outside of their respective domains, they must have nonzero residues everywhere. These additional properties hold also under certain natural regularity assumptions.
\label{thm:extreme_singular}
\end{theorem}
